## Azure Functions Standards
- Runtime: .NET 8 isolated worker (not in-process)
- Triggers: HTTP, Timer, Service Bus, Blob, Queue (match use case)
- Always async/await — never blocking calls
- Dependency injection via IServiceCollection in Program.cs
- Function timeout: set explicitly (default 5 min, max 10 min consumption plan)
- Durable Functions for long-running/orchestration workflows

```csharp
// ✅ Correct Azure Function pattern
[Function("CreateUser")]
public async Task<HttpResponseData> Run(
    [HttpTrigger(AuthorizationLevel.Function, "post")] HttpRequestData req,
    FunctionContext executionContext)
{
    var logger = executionContext.GetLogger<CreateUserFunction>();
    try {
        var request = await req.ReadFromJsonAsync<CreateUserRequest>();
        var result = await _userService.CreateAsync(request!);
        var response = req.CreateResponse(HttpStatusCode.Created);
        await response.WriteAsJsonAsync(new { success = true, data = result });
        return response;
    }
    catch (ValidationException ex) {
        var response = req.CreateResponse(HttpStatusCode.UnprocessableEntity);
        await response.WriteAsJsonAsync(new { success = false, error = ex.Message });
        return response;
    }
}
```

## Azure AD / Authentication Rules
- Use MSAL for token acquisition (never manual HTTP calls to token endpoint)
- App registrations: minimum required permissions (principle of least privilege)
- Client secrets: always in Azure Key Vault, never in code or config files
- Token caching: MSAL handles automatically — don't reinvent
- Conditional Access: document requirements in architecture notes

## Security Rules
- Managed Identity for all Azure-to-Azure authentication (no service principals with secrets)
- Key Vault references in App Settings (never store secrets as plain app settings)
- VNET integration for production (never expose functions directly to internet for internal APIs)
- API Management gateway for public-facing functions

## Cost Optimization Rules
- Consumption plan for event-driven, low-frequency functions
- Premium plan for functions needing VNET, always-warm, longer timeout
- Review Application Insights sampling rate (100% = expensive on high volume)
- Set budget alerts in Azure Cost Management
